<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/2604564-neva"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1442506927i/2604564._UX100_CR0,16,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/2604564-neva">Neva</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">No. It quotes some of them briefly in order to link some concepts and show some developments, but &quot;The Drowned and the Saved&quot; is a book on its own, on<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">No. It quotes some of them briefly in order to link some concepts and show some developments, but "The Drowned and the Saved" is a book on its own, one of Levi's best, and maybe his most mature. Highly recommended.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
