<div id="review_3536730537" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3536730537" />
    <a title="Sevda Grancharova" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2849550-sevda-grancharova"><img alt="Sevda Grancharova" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545056625p2/2849550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3536730537?book_show_action=true">Sep 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sevda Grancharova" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sevda Grancharova" href="/user/show/2849550-sevda-grancharova">Sevda Grancharova</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9786191865659" href="/book/show/52747494">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3536730537" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10331444083388843209">After almost 80 years, everything about the Holocaust seems a far away horror memory from the history books and black and white documentaries, that we, as a society, are not sure what to do with. <br/><br/>Few years ago I was in Warsaw for a work trip in the beginning of March and I took an extra day to walk around the city through historical points and museums, inevitably most of which, related to the jewish unfortunate fate during the second world war. It was cold like only Poland can be in March, every</span>
  <span id="freeText10331444083388843209" style="display:none">After almost 80 years, everything about the Holocaust seems a far away horror memory from the history books and black and white documentaries, that we, as a society, are not sure what to do with. <br /><br />Few years ago I was in Warsaw for a work trip in the beginning of March and I took an extra day to walk around the city through historical points and museums, inevitably most of which, related to the jewish unfortunate fate during the second world war. It was cold like only Poland can be in March, everything was grey, everything felt so miserable and walking past all those ghost buildings (they are not even buildings, but left-over walls, or just parts of buildings) made me feel for the first time on a trip - so honestly awful and even scared in a strange way, that after just a few hours I ran back to the hotel, grabbed my things and got a cab straight to the airport, half-a-day earlier for my flight. <br /><br />Reaching for Primo Levi's book is hard, because it's a book about a past far enough that we (the people from the future) accept not to understand and want to leave behind - "they were different", "life was different", "it's a long time ago". We "know the facts" and we've figured out all the excuses not to be interested "in the details". <br /><br />Still I got the book after reading few excerpts and reviews from people I like and often take book recommendations from. <br /><br />What I found was an almost philosophical view on human nature. It is a book about the Holocaust, it is a book about the camps, but in a much greater scale it is not a memoir, but an exquisite, brutally honest contemplation over our self-understanding as humans. It is in its core about our human abilities to drawn, to vanish into evil as perpetrators, as victims, as bystanders, as strong or weak. We are capable occasionally of empathy, compassion, sacrifices and heroism, but we are not only wired for that. And we have to constantly nourish "our good" to prevent "our evil". <br /><br />The whole book feels like a one-on-one conversation, a random acquaintance in the airplane with a stranger who opens up to you, so you feel you knew him all your life after you land. Even most reviewers say Levi is calm, I would say that you can sense (understandable) anger at places, you can feel the judgment sometimes, you can note some tiny moments of regret, of pity, of insult, but they are all just nuances of this deep, hard truth that the book carries. It's a special meeting with Primo Levi at the verge of his fortunate unfortunate life story and his own understanding of it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10331444083388843209" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


