<div id="review_90208229" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/90208229" />
    <a title="Natalie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3223035-natalie"><img alt="Natalie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606266271p2/3223035.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/90208229?book_show_action=true">Feb 17, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Natalie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Natalie" href="/user/show/3223035-natalie">Natalie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer90208229" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15777241196895822852">Wow. This novel is different from any other that I&apos;ve read on the Holocaust, and I&apos;ve read quite a few. Levi told his story through narrative in &quot;Survival in Auschwitz&quot; but in &quot;The Drowned and the Saved,&quot; he&apos;s taking a look back at that and his other works, and his experience in general. This book is worth reading for everyone because of Levi&apos;s articulate and well-thought out points about the Holocaust, but especially insightful for someone who&apos;s been interested in the subject in a long time and</span>
  <span id="freeText15777241196895822852" style="display:none">Wow. This novel is different from any other that I've read on the Holocaust, and I've read quite a few. Levi told his story through narrative in "Survival in Auschwitz" but in "The Drowned and the Saved," he's taking a look back at that and his other works, and his experience in general. This book is worth reading for everyone because of Levi's articulate and well-thought out points about the Holocaust, but especially insightful for someone who's been interested in the subject in a long time and wants a more philosophical viewpoint by a survivor. Never bitter and always logical, Levi's honesty shows through beautifully in his last masterpiece.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15777241196895822852" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


